
CSS selector (Cascading Style Sheet)

it is another way of locating elements on the web page

Syntax:
tagname[attribute='attribute value']
input[value='LOGIN']

Shortcuts for CSS only for ID and classes:
Shortcut for the classname --> "."
Syntax: tagname.classNameValue
    input.button

Shortcut for ID --> "#"
Syntax: tagname#idValue
input#txtPassword

contains() method in css:
* symbol is represent this method
tagname[attribute *= 'partial attribute value']
input[placeholder *= 'phone']

starts-with method in css:
^ symbol (Circumflex) represents this method
tagname[attribute ^= 'starting attribute value']
input[aria-label ^='Pass']

ends-with method in css:
tagname[attribute $= 'ending attribute value']
a[href $='login']

xPath vs CSS
-- CSS cannot locate the elements by text whereas xPath can
-- CSS has shortcuts
-- xPath doesn't have ends-with method
-- CSS is faster than xPath in locating elements
-- CSS has more simple syntax than xPath


WebElement Commands:
consist of several methods where we can perform an action and get the element state
on the webpage

isEnabled() --> boolean
isDisplayed() --> boolean
isSelected() --> boolean
clear() -- void
getText() --> String
getAttribute() --> String
submit() --> void
